{"type":"text","timestamp":1778566542295,"sessionID":"ses_1e533e93cffevPhFJXlgrQPI9F","part":{"id":"prt_e1ad3a74a001HDB0TrJEK2EkEQ","messageID":"msg_e1ad38c82001fTLcg8N5yKra2p","sessionID":"ses_1e533e93cffevPhFJXlgrQPI9F","type":"text","text":"I’ve written the hypothesis file to:\n\n`cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r1s0.yaml`\n\n**Summary:** The hypothesis adds a MEM-to-EX forwarding bypass for load data, eliminating the one-cycle load-use stall that currently costs IPC on every dependent instruction immediately following a load. By exporting the combinational `load_data` from `mem_stage` to the `ex_stage` operand mux and removing the load-use hazard from `hazard_unit`, dependent instructions can enter EX on the cycle right after the load enters MEM. Expected fitness delta is **+8 %** (medium confidence), driven entirely by IPC improvement with minimal Fmax risk because the existing critical path likely remains the combinational divider.","time":{"start":1778566539082,"end":1778566542294}}}
