{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778566947552,"sessionID":"ses_1e533e8dbffel9wB1drdOsErV0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"write:6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\ntitle: Replace combinational divider with iterative 32-cycle unit\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The baseline ALU implements DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU using combinational Verilog\n  `/` and `%` operators.  On the Tang Nano 20K this infers a massive\n  combinational subtract-and-multiplex tree that is almost certainly on the\n  critical path, limiting Fmax to 127 MHz (well below the 135 MHz target).\n  CoreMark is dominated by multiply-add and pointer-chasing; it contains no\n  dynamic division instructions, so making division multi-cycle has negligible\n  IPC cost for the fitness benchmark while removing the longest\n  combinational path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from the combinational ALU (non-ALTOPS path only;\n  keep the ALTOPS XOR substitutions so riscv-formal still matches).  Add a\n  new clocked iterative divider module (`divider.sv`) that computes a 32-bit\n  quotient or remainder in 32 cycles using a shift-and-subtract algorithm.\n  The EX stage detects a division opcode, starts the divider, and stalls the\n  pipeline (`stall_ex_mem`, `stall_id`, `stall_if`) while `divider.busy` is\n  high.  When the divider finishes its result is muxed into the EX/MEM\n  `alu_result` field exactly as before, so downstream MEM/WB logic is\n  unchanged.  Multiplication stays combinational (mapped to FPGA DSPs) and\n  is unaffected.  This structural change breaks the worst-case combinational\n  path and should raise Fmax by 10–20 % with no CoreMark IPC penalty.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 12\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: >\n      In the non-ALTOPS (`else`) branch, remove the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU case\n      arms so the ALU no longer contains combinational division logic.  Keep\n      the `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` XOR substitutions unchanged so formal\n      verification continues to match the spec.\n\n  - file: rtl/divider.sv\n    description: >\n      New 32-cycle iterative restoring/non-restoring divider module with\n      `start`, `busy`, `done`, `dividend`, `divisor`, `is_signed`, `rem_op`\n      inputs and a 32-bit `result` output.  Handles the RV32M special cases\n      (divide-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1) inside the module or in a thin\n      wrapper.\n\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: >\n      Instantiate the divider.  When `in.ctrl.alu_op` is DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU,\n      drive `alu_result` from the divider output instead of the ALU, assert\n      `divider_start`, and keep the EX/MEM register frozen via a new\n      `div_stall` signal until `divider_done` arrives.  Jumps and branches\n      continue to resolve normally; only the division instruction itself is\n      delayed.\n\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: >\n      Accept a new `div_busy` input.  Assert `stall_if`, `stall_id`, and\n      `stall_ex_mem` whenever `div_busy` is high so the entire pipeline\n      freezes around the in-flight division.\n\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: >\n      Remove the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU vectors from the ALU testbench (the ALU\n      no longer implements them).  Add a new `test_divider.py` or extend\n      the existing ALU test to instantiate `divider.sv` and verify exact\n      32-cycle bit-wise results for all four division operations including\n      the edge cases.\n","filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/kimi-k2_6-rep1/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778566947533,"end":1778566947550}},"id":"prt_e1ad96a83001rJKj0imVo2PCxu","sessionID":"ses_1e533e8dbffel9wB1drdOsErV0","messageID":"msg_e1ad838f0001HbjxaBmezV1d7K"}}
